  "prompt": "How has legislation evolved to combat money laundering?",
  "response": "Legislation to combat money laundering has evolved significantly over the past few decades:\n\n1. Early Stages\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970, USA)\n- First international recognition of money laundering as a criminal activity\n\n2. Key Milestones\n- FATF establishment (1989)\n- UN Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime (2000)\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001)\n\n3. Major Legislative Developments\n- Enhanced customer due diligence requirements\n- Mandatory transaction reporting\n- Stricter Know Your Customer (KYC) regulations\n- Increased international cooperation\n- Expanded definition of financial institutions\n- Harsher penalties for non-compliance\n\n4. Technological Adaptations\n- Regulations covering cryptocurrency\n- Digital transaction monitoring\n- Advanced anti-money laundering (AML) software\n- Cross-border information sharing mechanisms\n\n5. Recent Trends\n- Emphasis on beneficial ownership transparency\n- Risk-based approach to compliance\n- Enhanced sanctions screening\n- Increased focus on emerging financial technologies\n\n6. Global Standardization\n- Consistent regulatory frameworks\n- Multilateral agreements\n- Coordinated enforcement strategies\n\nThe legislation continues to evolve, driven by technological changes and emerging financial crime techniques.",
